article.description: Richard Jefferson scored 25 points and Vince Carter tipped in his own shot with 9.6 seconds left, giving the Nets a 95-94 win over the Bobcats.
article.headline: Carter's tip-in gives Nets win over Bobcats
article.linkText: Carter's tip-in gives Nets win over Bobcats
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Vince Carter took it upon himself to put an end to New Jersey's road woes. Richard Jefferson scored 25 points and Carter tipped in his own miss with 9.6 seconds left to the lift the Nets to a 95-94 win over the Charlotte Bobcats on Wednesday night. New Jersey snapped a seven-game road losing streak with the victory. The Bobcats, who trailed by as many as 18 in the first quarter, had a chance to win but Brevin Knight's leaner in the lane over Cliff Robinson hit off the front rim with 3 seconds left. "It was obviously a huge play with (Carter) being able to get his own miss and put it back," Nets coach Lawrence Frank said. "It was a game in which we obviously made our share of mistakes. But when you're struggling like we've been on the road, sometimes you just have to find a way to win the game." Nenad Krstic had 20 points and Carter scored 19 for New Jersey. Jason Kidd finished with 11 points, nine rebounds and nine assists for the Nets, who enter the All-Star break atop the Atlantic Division. Knight scored a game-high 28 points for Charlotte. Battling a chest cold, Carter came up big down the stretch. The Nets went his way on all three of their final offensive possessions, letting him work one-on-one against Matt Carroll. After Raymond Felton put the Bobcats up 92-91 with a short jumper with just over a minute to play, Carter put the Nets back on top with two free throws after drawing a blocking foul on Melvin Ely on a drive through the lane. The Bobcats came right back as Carroll canned a jumper from the wing with 16.1 seconds left to give Charlotte a 94-93 lead. Carter drove the lane again on the next possession and Ely came over to help. This time, the collision resulted in a no-call and Carter managed to outleap Ely to tip in his miss. "At the end I was just trying to get to the hole and get a call," Carter said. "As you can see I didn't get the call. So I was just trying to concentrate and make the shot. I just wanted to be aggressive." Knight said he was disappointed the Bobcats didn't get a call to go their way in the final minute. "It was the end of the game," Knight said. "The refs, especially for the Bobcats, they are going to make you win the game. There were a whole lot of calls that should have been different but we just have to live with that." The Nets hadn't won on the road since Jan. 18 and were lucky to escape with a win over the banged-up Bobcats, who simply refused to go away. The Bobcats were missing four of their big men, including starting center Primoz Brezec. Charlotte fell behind by 18 points in the first quarter but went on a 34-12 run. They took a 47-43 lead behind the play of Ely and Knight, who combined to score 19 points in the second quarter. That's nothing unusual for Knight, who seems to elevate his game when playing against Kidd. In three games this season against the Nets, Knight has averaged 25 points, more than double his season average of 12.3. He fell four points short of tying a career high. Jumaine Jones finished with 18 points and eight rebounds, while Ely had 13 points and nine rebounds for Charlotte. Frank said he pleased with his team's play in the first quarter, but disappointed they allowed an 18-point lead to slip away. "We didn't do a great job against their pressure," Frank said. "We had four empty possessions in a row. ... We had some open shots that we didn't make and we committed some turnovers because we couldn't make an open shot. Before you know it, it was a tie game." Despite the loss, Bobcats coach Bernie Bickerstaff was pleased with his team's play after lashing out at them following a loss Monday night to the Portland Trail Blazers. "The effort was much, much, much better," Bickerstaff said.

Game notes
Brezec sat out with a sore Achilles' heel and was replaced in the starting lineup by Jake Voskuhl. Brezec said he'll be back for Charlotte's next game on Tuesday. ... Bobcats coach Bernie Bickerstaff said he expects Gerald Wallace to return for Charlotte's first game after the break against Denver on Feb. 21. Wallace said he could have played against the Nets. "I wanted to play tonight, but I didn't want to push myself without a good practice," Wallace said. "I'm looking forward to the West coast trip." ... Charlotte has won 14 games in the first half of the season after winning just 11 in the first half of 2005.
